{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413108"},"attributes":{"position":4,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:56:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:56:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1773"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501652"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:31:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:31:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1773"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"1773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1773"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.27,0.63,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82860"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1773"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67963"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"348"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"692"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9682"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82860"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 45-minute history of left-sided visual loss and headache. She has never had these symptoms before. She describes some arm paraesthesia but denies arm or leg weakness, bladder or bowel symptoms. Her eye movements are not painful. The headache is mild (4/10) and located on the right side above her ear. She has a history of epilepsy and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Initial neurological examination demonstrated difficulty seeing in the left visual field of both eyes, however while in the department her symptoms resolved completely after 45 minutes. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal. A computed tomography brain scan and angiogram are unremarkable, except for 50% stenosis in both carotid arteries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complex migraine","Amaurosis fugax","Transient ischaemic attack","Todd\u0027s paralysis","Carotid artery dissection"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely cause of this patient\u0027s presentation is a \u003Cstrong\u003Etransient ischaemic attack (TIA)\u003C/strong\u003E. Traditionally, TIA was defined as occurring within 24 hours followed by a full recovery - the new tissue based definition defines TIA as having neurological symptoms without acute infarction or evidence of permanent injury. While headache can occur in TIA (present in up to 36% of cases), it is typically mild and non-specific as seen here, unlike the severe throbbing headache characteristic of migraine. The bilateral visual field deficits with paraesthesia suggest a posterior circulation TIA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk stratification using the ABCD2 score (Age \u226560=1, BP \u2265140/90=1, Clinical features: unilateral weakness=2 or speech disturbance without weakness=1, Duration \u226560min=2 or 10-59min=1, Diabetes=1) helps determine urgency of investigation and management. This patient would be considered moderate risk and requires urgent outpatient investigation within 24-48 hours including carotid doppler, ECG and echocardiogram.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplex migraines\u003C/strong\u003E are atypical migraines with aura causing symptoms such as temporary hemi-paralysis in addition to more typical migraine symptoms. Patients suffering from migraine typically complain of a severe, pulsating, boring or hammering headache that is often unilateral and associated with photophobia, phonophobia, and nausea. The mild nature of this patient\u0027s headache and lack of typical migraine features makes complex migraine unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmaurosis fugax\u003C/strong\u003E occurs as a result of stenosis of the internal carotid artery or central retinal artery. While TIAs and strokes can often be preceded by amaurosis fugax, the transient vision loss that occurs in amaurosis fugax is often unilateral and isn\u0027t accompanied by other symptoms such as paraesthesia as in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETodd\u0027s paralysis\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs after focal seizures and is the postictal weakness or paralysis of the involved limb or facial muscles. It can last for minutes or up to 36 hours. The lack of symptoms suggestive of a focal seizure such as motor symptoms (e.g. clonus, myoclonus, atony, Jacksonian march) makes this an unlikely option. Post-ictal headache is typically more severe and diffuse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid artery dissection\u003C/strong\u003E can occur spontaneously or from trauma. While it is possible it can result in impaired perfusion to the brain, it is unlikely it would resolve as it did in this patient. Furthermore, a CT brain and angiogram would normally detect carotid artery dissections. Carotid dissection typically causes severe, unilateral neck pain or headache.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The diagnosis of TIA is based upon clinical symptoms and lack of features of infarction on neuroimaging","Bilateral visual symptoms with associated neurological features suggest posterior circulation TIA","ABCD2 score stratifies TIA patients into low, moderate and high risk for subsequent stroke"],"references":["Sacco RL, Kasner SE, Broderick JP, Caplan LR, Connors JJ, Culebras A, et al. An updated definition of stroke for the 21st century: a statement for healthcare professionals from the American Heart Association/American Stroke Association. Stroke. 2013;44(7):2064-89.","Charles J, Pan Y, Miller G. TIAs Management in general practice. Australian Family Physician. 2010;39:813-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67963"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1773"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{